					</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">&lsquo;Death to America&rsquo; in Perspective</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Carol Giacomo			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-02-12T19:30:11+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">February 12, 2014 2:30 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">February 12, 2014 2:30 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//takingnote.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/02/12/death-to-america-in-perspective/" data-title="&lsquo;Death to America&rsquo; in Perspective" data-description="Despite extremist rhetoric, most Iranians are not eager for another war. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div>
<div class="w480"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/02/12/opinion/2122014iran/2122014iran-blog480.jpg" id="100000002707242" width="480" height="320" alt="Iranians marked the 35th anniversary of the Islamic revolution on Feb. 11, 2014.&nbsp;" /><span class="credit">Atta Kenare/Agence France-Presse â Getty Images</span><span class="caption">Iranians marked the 35th anniversary of the Islamic revolution on Feb. 11, 2014.&nbsp;</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For many Americans, the familiar chants of âdeath to Americaâ on the 35<sup>th</sup> anniversary of the Iranian Islamic revolution on Tuesday were no doubt infuriating. How can the United States ever complete a nuclear deal, much less consider normalizing relations in the future, with such a relentlessly hostile country?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Itâs a fair question.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As The Timesâs <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/12/world/middleeast/anniversary-of-islamic-revolution-in-iran.html?hpw&amp;rref=world//www.nytimes.com/2014/02/12/world/middleeast/anniversary-of-islamic-revolution-in-iran.html?hpw&amp;rref=world">Thomas Erdbrink reported</a>, the largest anniversary day rallies, which took place in Tehran, featured posters and placards with anti-American themes. Some referred to Secretary of State John Kerryâs recent assertion that the military option is still âavailable to the United Statesâ if negotiations falter.<br />
<span id="more-16113"></span><br />
âWe are eager for all options on the table,â many of the placards read, while others claimed, âWe are ready for the great battle.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The exhortations do not inspire confidence, but they are to a great extent political theater and need to be seen in that context. As I discovered after spending 10 days in Iran in December, the situation is more textured when viewed from the ground.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Iranian politics is a stew. There are clearly many Iranians who hate the United States and want to see the nuclear deal and any future rapprochement fail. This includes the Revolutionary Guard, hardline lawmakers and their allies in the media, among others. The 1979 revolution was built on an anti-American, anti-Western narrative, and for the true believers preserving that theme is synonymous with preserving the revolutionâs promise.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But most Iranians last year voted to elect President Hassan Rouhani who has made negotiations with the United States a signature issue. His supporters are eager to see the negotiations succeed so that international sanctions can be lifted and Iran can revive its devastated economy through economic and political reintegration with the world.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It is also apparent that, despite the extremist rhetoric, most Iranians are not eager for another war. They paid a huge price during the war with Iraq in 1980-1988, when Saddam Hussein killed thousands of Kurds and other Iranians with chemical weapons. That legacy haunts them still. Dr. Shahriar Khateri, the countryâs leading expert on chemical weapons, told me that 70,000 Iranians are today still suffering â and dying â from the effects. One victim whom I visited at a hospital in Tehran died on Monday.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When listening to the âdeath to Americaâ chants, itâs important to remember that there is plenty of muscular rhetoric from Washington as well. In Congress, many lawmakers have been pushing for a new round of even more punishing sanctions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Proponents of a deal on both sides will have to tune out the rhetoric and keep their focus on the facts. If they can reach a comprehensive nuclear agreement, and adhere to its terms, they can build trust. And eventually, perhaps, the chanting will fade away.</p>
	</div>
